00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:53.520
[Amit Varma]: Sujata, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:54.520
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:55.520
[Amit Varma]: My pleasure.

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:58.520
[Amit Varma]: I've been following you, as I mentioned in my intro since the 1990s.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:03.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, while many of the finest political reporters today are women, back in the day,

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:07.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, you were almost an exception in that sense, because there was this feeling

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:12.400
[Amit Varma]: that in journalism, women do the soft beat, they do the features, they do all of that.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:14.560
[Amit Varma]: And you were a proper hardcore political reporter.

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:16.880
[Guest]: How did you get into journalism and reporting?

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:21.480
[Guest]: I basically took a journalism course because I wanted to join the IAS.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:26.120
[Guest]: And I thought taking a journalism course will teach me essay writing, which had a lot of

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:27.440
[Guest]: marks on that.

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:31.680
[Guest]: But once I went into journalism, I never looked back and I didn't want to become an IAS officer.

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:34.560
[Guest]: I wanted to continue as a journalist.

00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:39.040
[Guest]: Political journalism, I applied for a job to Times of India.

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:45.040
[Guest]: And there the editor told me that, you know, I was writing on Rotary clubs, Lions clubs,

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.080
[Guest]: you know, dance shows, things like that.

00:04:47.080 --> 00:04:50.320
[Guest]: What you said, you know, I mean, soft journalism, entertainment.

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:54.120
[Guest]: And he saw my portfolio and he said that if this is the kind of journalism you want to

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:59.440
[Guest]: do, I suggest you go and start teaching English at Elphinstone College, because you can still

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:03.680
[Guest]: continue to do this in your spare time, you know, I mean, but if you want to be a real

00:05:03.680 --> 00:05:08.200
[Guest]: journalist, you have to choose either business journalism or political journalism.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:13.360
[Guest]: Now, I didn't have a head for business journalism, you know, so I got pushed into political journalism

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:14.820
[Guest]: against my will.

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:17.680
[Guest]: But once I was there, I realized my editor was right.

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:22.640
[Guest]: He said that I was a natural and I realized that I was indeed a natural in political journalism.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:25.400
[Amit Varma]: And were you already interested in politics in general?

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:27.840
[Amit Varma]: Or is that something you had to cultivate after you?

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:28.840
[Guest]: No, I was not.

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:33.080
[Guest]: In fact, I hated politics at that point of time, which is why I was doing the soft entertainment

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:34.160
[Guest]: journalism.

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:38.440
[Guest]: But when I began my career, there was nothing like entertainment journalism, you know, I

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:42.840
[Guest]: mean, I always tell people that had there been entertainment journalism at that time,

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:47.000
[Guest]: I would have been an entertainment editor rather than a political editor by this time,

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.720
[Guest]: you know, I mean, but I got pushed into it against my will.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:54.680
[Guest]: I hated it in the first few months in the first couple of years.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:06:00.040
[Guest]: But once I got the hang of it, I think I was able to understand the political nuances much

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:01.880
[Amit Varma]: better than many other people.

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:05.200
[Amit Varma]: And what was it like in those early days, like, you know, when you're going out on the

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:08.040
[Amit Varma]: beat, you're meeting politicians, did they take you seriously?

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:09.040
[Amit Varma]: How did they treat you?

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:13.640
[Amit Varma]: How do you learn to sort of talk in their kind of language and have them open up to

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:14.640
[Guest]: you?

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:18.120
[Guest]: You know, when I started out, like you said earlier, there were very few women in the

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:19.120
[Guest]: field.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:22.320
[Guest]: A couple of them were there before me, Olga Telles was there, you know, I mean, I think

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:29.000
[Guest]: she was the first political woman correspondent, and a couple more in Marathi journalism.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.400
[Guest]: And many of us who were covering active politics, like having to visit Mantralaya, having to

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:38.600
[Guest]: visit the Legislative Assembly during sessions, we had a real battle on our hands in the beginning,

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:43.360
[Guest]: because you know, the legislators, the MLAs coming from villages, coming from small towns,

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:48.680
[Guest]: they were just not used to seeing, you know, women in such freedom modes, you know, I mean,

00:06:48.680 --> 00:06:52.480
[Guest]: like we were free, we were coming there, we were talking, we were laughing, you know,

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:57.320
[Guest]: I mean, we were taking our place equally amongst the men, and they just couldn't get over that.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:01.560
[Guest]: So many of them thought that we were up for some game.

00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:06.560
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they made passes at us, you know, I mean, and they tried to get a

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:11.200
[Guest]: lot more serious, but then all of us, all the women journalists, we really put them

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:15.000
[Guest]: in their place, you know, I mean, there was one senior woman journalist who took me under

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:16.000
[Guest]: her wing.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.160
[Guest]: And she said, whenever these MLAs come close to me, and they put their face close to me,

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:27.080
[Guest]: and say, kai bai, kai chal laa hai, so I tell them, bai nai, tai mana.

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:31.480
[Guest]: You know that I'm your elder sister, you know, I mean, I'm not just another woman.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:36.600
[Guest]: And I tell them keep a distance of at least five feet from where you're standing and talking

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:37.600
[Guest]: to me.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:40.240
[Guest]: And you should also be very careful about this.

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:43.080
[Guest]: But you know, she was one of the pioneers.

00:07:43.080 --> 00:07:45.500
[Guest]: So she had cleared the way quite a lot.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:49.840
[Guest]: By the time I came into journalism, yes, there were some ministers, there were some MLAs

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:51.640
[Guest]: who tried to make passes.

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:54.920
[Guest]: But I knew how to deal with it, you know, I put them in their place.

00:07:54.920 --> 00:08:00.120
[Guest]: And once they got to know, once they got to know that you were not up for all these things,

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:02.320
[Guest]: then they began to take you very seriously.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And also, I guess language was never a problem for you.

00:08:04.680 --> 00:08:08.560
[Amit Varma]: Because like you mentioned, before we started our conversation, you've pretty much grown

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:12.600
[Amit Varma]: up here, though, and you said you've come from MP, where you were born.

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And isn't that something you have in common with Mr. Thackeray's father, Keshav Thackeray

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:18.120
[Guest]: also came from MP to Maharashtra.

00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:22.120
[Guest]: Yes, he did come from MP to Maharashtra, but he actually migrated.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:23.120
[Guest]: I was born there.

00:08:23.120 --> 00:08:28.240
[Guest]: My father was posted in Amarnath, close to close to Mumbai, you know, I mean, he was

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:31.360
[Guest]: with the defense services, you know, I mean, so I was born there.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:34.000
[Guest]: And then I came here, I grew up here.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:39.000
[Guest]: And well, but yes, I am a migrant, just like, just like the Thackerays, you know, I mean,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.600
[Guest]: I am a migrant.

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:46.320
[Guest]: But Maharashtra government, particularly, I don't know whether this is true about other

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:52.640
[Guest]: states, it considers that if you have lived in Maharashtra continuously for 20 years,

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:57.760
[Guest]: you have to be regarded as a native, you are a regular Maharashtrian, you know, I mean,

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:04.040
[Guest]: so by that definition, I am a Maharashtrian, I'm an honorary Maharashtrian.

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:07.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, I really enjoyed reading both your books, especially in Maharashtra Maximus,

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:13.120
[Amit Varma]: which has come out recently is especially fascinating, because it sort of puts the fault

00:09:13.120 --> 00:09:18.240
[Amit Varma]: lines in current Maharashtra politics in very sharp historical perspective.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:21.880
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, when people talk about contemporary politics, they'll talk about

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: the Brahmins versus Marathas and so on.

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And reading your book, I realized that this is a fault line that is not something that

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.840
[Amit Varma]: only in modern politics, it goes back hundreds of years.

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:36.420
[Amit Varma]: Tell us a little bit more about that, about, you know, the schism between the two that

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:39.240
[Amit Varma]: sort of happened when the Peshwas took over from Shivaji.

00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:48.160
[Guest]: Yeah, now, Shivaji was a Maratha warrior king, and his son, Sambhaji, and grandson, Shahu

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:49.160
[Guest]: Maharaj.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:54.160
[Guest]: You know, until then, it was the Bhosle dynasty, which had a tight grip on Maharashtra.

00:09:54.160 --> 00:10:00.480
[Guest]: But right from the times of Shivaji, Vishwanath Ballal was their Peshwa, their prime minister.

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:05.080
[Guest]: And after that, after Shahuji, there was a split in the family.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:08.000
[Guest]: They were two sons, you know, I mean, there were two branches of the family.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:14.400
[Guest]: Tara Bai, who was the second wife, you know, she wanted the inheritance for her son, Rajaram.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:17.840
[Guest]: And of course, Shahu Maharaj was under the custody of Aurangzeb.

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:20.320
[Guest]: Aurangzeb had kidnapped him and his mother.

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:24.400
[Guest]: Then he got released, and he came and he sat on the throne.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.480
[Guest]: But by that time, there was a split in the dynasty.

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:32.120
[Guest]: So there was one branch ruling out of Kolhapur, and one branch ruling out of Satara.

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:38.280
[Guest]: Now the Peshwas, the prime ministers, the Ballal family, they took advantage of this.

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:42.840
[Guest]: And while they ruled in the name of the Maratha kings, they were the actual warriors.

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:45.960
[Guest]: Now they were Brahmins, and they were not a warrior caste.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:50.040
[Guest]: For those centuries, for those days, you know, I mean, they were not expected to go into

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:51.520
[Guest]: the battlefield.

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:57.880
[Guest]: But Bajirao particularly, Bajirao Ballal, he is one general who never lost a battle,

00:10:57.880 --> 00:10:59.520
[Guest]: who never lost a war.

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:02.400
[Guest]: He died early, but he never lost a war.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:07.520
[Guest]: And of course, the Marathas had a very guerrilla kind of fighting, you know, they never used

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:12.320
[Guest]: to have open battles, which is why the first open battle that they ever had, which was

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:14.240
[Guest]: the Panipat in 1761.

00:11:14.240 --> 00:11:21.280
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they lost that war, because they really could not fight that on open ground.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:26.640
[Guest]: And but until Bajirao was alive, he never lost a single war.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:32.160
[Guest]: And the Marathas, when we refer to Marathas, we also mean the Peshwas.

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:36.720
[Guest]: But this Maratha Peshwa dynasty, I mean, that war that they lost, the battle of the war

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:40.280
[Guest]: of Panipat that they lost, it pushed them back by a whole generation.

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:44.160
[Guest]: 20-25 years, they could not do anything.

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:50.480
[Guest]: Then gradually, gradually the succeeding dynasties by that time, Shivaji's descendants were just

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:55.120
[Guest]: rubber stamps, if I may put it like that, you know, I mean, they were just putting the

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:58.400
[Guest]: mohary on all the decisions of the Peshwas.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:05.560
[Guest]: And the inheritors of Bajirao Ballal, the heirs of Bajirao Ballal, they gradually built

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:07.120
[Guest]: up the dynasty again.

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:10.840
[Guest]: But they were a weakened lot and there was a lot of infighting amongst them after Bajirao's

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:15.360
[Guest]: death, you know, his brother, his nephews, everybody, they wanted a piece of the cake

00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:16.360
[Guest]: and things like that.

00:12:16.360 --> 00:12:18.480
[Guest]: So the dynasty was highly weakened.

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:23.280
[Guest]: And if you go back in history, Charles Metcalfe, Lord Charles Metcalfe, who was the governor

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:28.640
[Guest]: of Bombay, I think he had said that there are only two ruling powers in India.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:31.640
[Guest]: One is the British and the other are Marathas.

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:36.960
[Guest]: And every territory they cede, we occupy and every territory we occupy is ceded to us by

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:38.080
[Guest]: the Marathas.

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:43.200
[Guest]: So they were really ruling from north to south, from east to west, everywhere there was a

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:47.160
[Guest]: Maratha presence and they had gone as far back as Peshawar.

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:52.240
[Guest]: And I believe that if they had not lost the Battle of Panipat, if they had not lost the

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:56.520
[Guest]: War of Panipat, maybe we would not have had a partition of India also, because there would

00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:59.000
[Guest]: have been a Maratha rule over there.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.800
[Guest]: And we may not have had the partition of Bengal, because again, there would have been Maratha

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:04.800
[Guest]: domination over there.

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:07.120
[Guest]: But Marathas were pushed back from all the edges.

00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, this is very interesting.

00:13:08.480 --> 00:13:12.480
[Amit Varma]: Like again, bound by, you know, what we know of present day geography, people don't often

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:16.320
[Amit Varma]: realize how large the Maratha Empire was at its peak, like you point out from Peshawar

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:23.160
[Amit Varma]: to Tanjore and all the way to Bengal in the east and Gujarat in the west.

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:26.240
[Amit Varma]: Another interesting phrase I picked up from your book, like I've spoken to many historians

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:31.080
[Amit Varma]: on the show and some of them have told me about how Shivaji's sort of kind of nationalism

00:13:31.080 --> 00:13:36.040
[Amit Varma]: was an early version of the sort of Hindutva nationalism that we see today.

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And in your book, I learned the phrase Maharashtra dharma.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:43.520
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote from your book where you say, quote, Maharashtra dharma simplified for those

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:48.480
[Amit Varma]: unfamiliar with the term, meant not just Hindu dharma, but also nationalism.

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:54.160
[Amit Varma]: It manifested in 17th century India in various ways, such as a protection of the cow, protection

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:59.600
[Amit Varma]: of Brahmins, a fight for independence from Muslim kings, and an attempt to restore morality

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:04.720
[Amit Varma]: in Indian Hindu society, which many felt had been destroyed by the Islamic rulers, stop

00:14:04.720 --> 00:14:05.720
[Amit Varma]: quote.

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:09.640
[Amit Varma]: I almost feel like this is, you know, like, it's the same, right?

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:10.640
[Guest]: In a sense.

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:11.720
[Guest]: Yes, it is.

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:15.960
[Guest]: And I received a lot of flack for writing that, you know, I mean, and people could not

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:19.720
[Guest]: accept there were lots of arguments, you know, during my book launch, etc, you know, saying

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:21.760
[Guest]: that they didn't agree with this.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:27.840
[Guest]: But you know, see, Shivaji had a royal saint, you know, all kings have their own resident

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:30.560
[Guest]: saints and all that, which was Ram Dass.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:37.760
[Guest]: And it was Ram Dass's campaign to restore all these old traditional ancient values,

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:38.760
[Guest]: etc.

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:44.400
[Guest]: But Shivaji on his own, one must accept, you know, I mean, his closest generals, his most

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:48.720
[Guest]: trusted generals were Muslims, his bodyguard was a Muslim.

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:52.800
[Guest]: And when he went out to meet Afzal Khan, you know, it was a Muslim bodyguard who warned

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:56.560
[Guest]: him that there is some conspiracy afoot and you better be careful because they might be

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:57.560
[Guest]: killing you.

00:14:57.560 --> 00:15:02.400
[Guest]: And Afzal Khan's conspirator was a Maharashtrian Brahmin.

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:07.160
[Guest]: So there were really no straight lines dividing the Muslims from the Hindus.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:10.440
[Guest]: But yes, they wanted their cultural values to be restored.

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:15.560
[Guest]: And Shivaji's campaign was for a Hindvi Swaraj.

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:22.880
[Guest]: That means an Indian self-rule, not like Hindutva Vadi, not exactly the Hindutva Vadi that we

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:23.880
[Guest]: are facing today.

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:29.960
[Guest]: You know, I mean, today it is only majoritarianism, it is only Hindutva, which is where I distinguish

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:34.080
[Guest]: today in modern day also, I distinguish Hinduism from Hindutva, you know, I mean, which is

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:35.080
[Guest]: very different.

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:40.680
[Guest]: Hindutva is a political philosophy, is a political philosophy and Hinduism is a religion.

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:46.080
[Guest]: But Chhatrapati Shivaji had no problems taking advice from Muslim generals, having Muslim

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.560
[Guest]: generals in his army, they used to lead him into battle, etc.

00:15:49.560 --> 00:15:52.280
[Guest]: So there was no communal divide at that point of time.

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:56.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's interesting that obviously Hindutva, like you correctly said, is a sort

00:15:56.600 --> 00:16:01.320
[Amit Varma]: of a political philosophy that the way I had understood it goes back to the early 20th

00:16:01.320 --> 00:16:08.440
[Amit Varma]: century is basically Savarkar, RSS, Gita Press, all of that happening in the 1910s, 1920s,

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:09.440
[Amit Varma]: around that period.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:14.280
[Amit Varma]: So I was sort of very intrigued to find earlier articulations of it, such as sort of Shivaji's

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:16.040
[Amit Varma]: muscular nationalism.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:20.400
[Amit Varma]: And I guess even as Hindvi Swaraj, the way he understood it, self-rule by the people

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:25.880
[Amit Varma]: here excluded the Mughal rulers and the Islamic rulers from that, from his understanding of

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:28.360
[Amit Varma]: what, you know, what our nation is, right?

00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:34.040
[Guest]: You know, Shivaji was in Pune, you know, he inherited a patch of land from his father

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:41.280
[Guest]: in Pune, which then one of his, what do you say, Acharyas, I could say, you know, I mean,

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:44.920
[Guest]: he helped him because Shivaji was a child at that point of time and Shivaji's father

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:47.040
[Guest]: was also separated from his mother.

00:16:47.040 --> 00:16:52.360
[Guest]: He was married a second time and he was with the Islamic kingdoms in the south, in the

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:55.200
[Guest]: Deccan, you know, he was a general in that kingdom.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:17:00.040
[Guest]: And Shivaji was quashed between Mughals in the north and these Deccan Islamic kingdoms

00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:01.360
[Guest]: in the south.

00:17:01.360 --> 00:17:03.920
[Guest]: And he was in Pune, which was a really wild patch of land.

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:08.760
[Guest]: There were wolves, there were hyenas in what we know as Pune today.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:12.840
[Guest]: And a reward was given, you know, people said that if you can come and you can clear this

00:17:12.840 --> 00:17:16.400
[Guest]: patch of the hyenas and wolves and everything, we will set up a kingdom here.

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:19.920
[Guest]: So a lot of farmers came and cleared that place, etc.

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:22.520
[Guest]: And then he set up his kingdom over there.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:26.360
[Guest]: And he had a very difficult task, you know, I mean, squashed between these two sides.

00:17:26.360 --> 00:17:30.560
[Guest]: But then he did make friends with the Deccan Islamic kingdoms.

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:33.480
[Guest]: Even if they were not very good friends, you know, they had an understanding, they had

00:17:33.480 --> 00:17:35.700
[Guest]: a military understanding.

00:17:35.700 --> 00:17:39.440
[Guest]: But the Mughals were really enemies because, you know, they kidnapped him.

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:45.560
[Guest]: And even there, Raja Jai Singh, who was sent to kidnap Shivaji, he was a Rajput, he was

00:17:45.560 --> 00:17:48.680
[Guest]: a Hindu Rajput and he was working on behalf of Aurangzeb.

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:52.400
[Guest]: And Aurangzeb kidnapped him, kept him in the Agra fort, etc.

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:53.640
[Guest]: He escaped from there, you know.

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:58.280
[Guest]: So there was a big history between him and Aurangzeb and then Sambhaji, his son and Aurangzeb,

00:17:58.280 --> 00:17:59.280
[Guest]: etc.

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:01.400
[Guest]: Sambhaji was put to death by Aurangzeb.

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And reportedly one of the reasons was he refused to name the Mughals who helped him.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:10.640
[Guest]: Yes, the collaborators, including Aurangzeb's son, who was in Sambhaji's army.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:13.780
[Guest]: You know, he refused to give away his position.

00:18:13.780 --> 00:18:18.560
[Guest]: And Sambhaji's position was given away by a Maratha general, you know, the More family.

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:24.240
[Guest]: So these things, you know, are, what do you say, they're not etched in sharp black and

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:29.080
[Guest]: white lines, you know, I mean, it keeps moving between various things.

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:30.840
[Amit Varma]: No, it's very interesting.

00:18:30.840 --> 00:18:34.400
[Amit Varma]: And there also you see traces of what you see in contemporary politics, where no matter

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:39.320
[Amit Varma]: how strongly an ideology is stated, eventually you make friends and enemies of convenience.

00:18:39.320 --> 00:18:42.000
[Guest]: Yes, yes, you do.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:50.680
[Guest]: And you know, that way Balasaheb Thackeray is seen as a very sharp, vicious, violent

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:52.720
[Guest]: Hindutva wadi.

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:59.600
[Guest]: But it is interesting that his party was set up in 1966.

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:04.440
[Guest]: And the first time that he sort of won the municipal corporation elections, he won it

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:06.840
[Guest]: on the issue of Vande Mataram.

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:11.040
[Guest]: Because that time, right from then, a Muslim corporator from the Congress had said that

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:13.480
[Guest]: I cannot sing Vande Mataram.

00:19:13.480 --> 00:19:16.320
[Guest]: And Thackeray was looking for this issue to go to the polls.

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:18.840
[Guest]: And so he just seized on Vande Mataram.

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:22.080
[Guest]: And he had a very vicious campaign against the Muslims.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:25.000
[Guest]: But still he did not win a majority in the BMC.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:29.880
[Guest]: And now to form a standing committee, he needed the support of two or three more corporators.

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:31.800
[Guest]: Who do you think he goes to?

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:35.440
[Guest]: He goes to GM Banatwala of the Indian Union Muslim League.

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:38.200
[Guest]: You know, you have just fought against that party.

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:42.520
[Guest]: You have called them names, but neither Banatwala nor Bal Thackeray have any problem joining

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:45.120
[Guest]: hands and becoming part of the standing committee.

00:19:45.120 --> 00:19:49.960
[Guest]: And this kind of a thing has now continued into this century, into this decade.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:53.320
[Guest]: You know, I mean, anybody who thinks it is politically convenient.

00:19:53.320 --> 00:19:56.680
[Guest]: Years ago, I had Madhavrao Sindhia.

00:19:56.680 --> 00:20:00.760
[Guest]: The late Madhavrao Sindhia used to be the General Secretary in charge of Maharashtra.

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:03.480
[Guest]: And it was Vajpayee's government in the center.

00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:06.840
[Guest]: So then I had said that, well, if they don't prove a majority, then they will have to resign

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:08.280
[Guest]: and there will be elections.

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:11.280
[Guest]: So he said, I don't have any hopes of that, you know, because they will break the other

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:15.480
[Guest]: political parties and anybody, you know, who's getting a little slice of power will go with

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:16.480
[Guest]: them.

00:20:16.480 --> 00:20:17.480
[Guest]: And so I said, what about ideology?

00:20:17.480 --> 00:20:18.720
[Guest]: So he said, ideology doesn't matter.

00:20:18.720 --> 00:20:20.940
[Guest]: It is only power that matters.

00:20:20.940 --> 00:20:24.080
[Guest]: So that is exactly what is happening even today.

00:20:24.080 --> 00:20:28.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, another interesting example of Thackeray, and of course, we'll speak about him more

00:20:28.320 --> 00:20:33.600
[Amit Varma]: later in this episode, is he had the India Pakistan match stopped where he had the pitch

00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:35.840
[Unknown]: at Wankhede dug up in 91.

00:20:35.840 --> 00:20:39.960
[Amit Varma]: And yet, not long after that, he's hanging out with Javed Mian Dada and saying, oh, don't

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:42.400
[Amit Varma]: worry, we'll have more matches here and all of that.

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:49.560
[Amit Varma]: So in private, it's one thing in public, another thing and let's kind of sort of, you know,

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:55.200
[Amit Varma]: go back into history and sort of talk about, you know, the birth of the shaping of Bombay

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:56.200
[Amit Varma]: itself.

00:20:56.200 --> 00:21:00.180
[Amit Varma]: In fact, like it's very interesting, like, you know, you had a lot of nativist claims

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:06.440
[Amit Varma]: made about Bombay in the last few decades by Thackeray and others, but the interesting

00:21:06.440 --> 00:21:10.720
[Amit Varma]: thing about Bombay is that its origin is actually very syncretic.

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:14.840
[Amit Varma]: And you know, it was basically two islands owned by Sultan Muhammad Shah.

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:17.560
[Amit Varma]: He gives that to the Portuguese.

00:21:17.560 --> 00:21:21.520
[Amit Varma]: The Portuguese give it as dowry to the British when Prince Charles marries Catherine of Braganza

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:23.720
[Amit Varma]: in 1662.

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And then the British don't really know what to do there.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.640
[Amit Varma]: And there are, you know, Kohli fishermen on those islands and there's not much, but then

00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:35.520
[Amit Varma]: it becomes a good port for shipping cotton and they set up cotton mills and Bombay becomes,

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:39.240
[Amit Varma]: as you point out, a mini Manchester of the East.

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:43.120
[Amit Varma]: And what happens interestingly there is that all the migrant labor brought in is from other

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:45.880
[Amit Varma]: rural parts of Maharashtra and from elsewhere.

00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So it isn't as if the original ingredients were necessarily Marathi.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:51.760
[Guest]: It's just a mix of all of these.

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:52.760
[Guest]: Yes, it is a mix.

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:56.880
[Guest]: You know, see Surat was a port right from Mughal times.

00:21:56.880 --> 00:22:00.640
[Guest]: You know, they used to sail their ships from there, they had to go to Hajj etc.

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:03.440
[Guest]: So they used to sail from Surat.

00:22:03.440 --> 00:22:08.280
[Guest]: And the British also used Surat, Portuguese also used that port, Dutch also used that

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:09.280
[Guest]: port.

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:13.920
[Guest]: But then the British came into these seven islands of Bombay and they joined them together

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:17.960
[Guest]: and they realized this strategically it was a very good port for military purposes and

00:22:17.960 --> 00:22:20.040
[Guest]: also for commercial purposes.

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:27.520
[Guest]: So when the importance shifted from Surat and Porbandar to Bombay, then there were a

00:22:27.520 --> 00:22:34.640
[Guest]: lot of Gujarati, Hindu, Jain, Sindhis, Marwadis, Bora Muslims, Parsis etc.

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:38.440
[Guest]: You know, I mean, shifting quickly towards Bombay and they were amongst the first ones

00:22:38.440 --> 00:22:40.860
[Guest]: to set up the textile mills etc.

00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:44.360
[Guest]: And all said and done, yes, there were these Kohli fishermen and there was a migrant labor

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:46.800
[Guest]: from interior of Maharashtra.

00:22:46.800 --> 00:22:52.360
[Guest]: But Bombay was actually built up by the Gujaratis, which is the core of the fight between the

00:22:52.360 --> 00:22:54.320
[Guest]: Maharashtrians and the Gujaratis at the moment.

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:59.520
[Guest]: So when after independence, this became a Bombay state, it was a bilingual state, Parsi

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:02.640
[Guest]: Saurashtra and Kutch were in Bombay state.

00:23:02.640 --> 00:23:07.360
[Guest]: And you know, the first chief minister of Bombay state was a Maharashtrian, but Muraji

00:23:07.360 --> 00:23:09.480
[Guest]: Desai was the second chief minister.

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:13.040
[Guest]: And there were these, you know, we talk about the Gujarati duo at the moment, you know,

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:18.120
[Guest]: Narendra Modi and Amit Shah, but there was also a Gujarati duo in the 50s, you know,

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:24.200
[Guest]: I mean, which was Vallabhbhai Patel and Muraji Desai, you know, who were accused of having

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:27.480
[Guest]: overdue influence on Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru.

00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:32.560
[Guest]: And Nehru preferred to listen to Sardar Patel and to Muraji Desai rather than to YB Chavan

00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:35.440
[Guest]: and the other Maharashtrian leaders.

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:40.440
[Guest]: And there was this movement, you know, I mean, for separating the two and all the Maharashtrian

00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:45.320
[Guest]: leaders complained that whatever the funds are allocated to the Bombay state, these strong

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:49.040
[Guest]: Gujarati leaders divert that towards Saurashtra and Kutch.

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:50.040
[Guest]: We don't get anything.

00:23:50.040 --> 00:23:51.480
[Guest]: Western Maharashtra doesn't get anything.

00:23:51.480 --> 00:23:56.600
[Guest]: Vidarbha at that point of time was with Madhya Pradesh, with Mahakosha and Marathwada was

00:23:56.600 --> 00:23:58.280
[Guest]: still with the Nizam of Hyderabad.

00:23:58.280 --> 00:24:00.320
[Guest]: It was part of Hyderabad state.

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:02.920
[Guest]: So Western Maharashtra and Bombay were with Bombay state.

00:24:02.920 --> 00:24:07.200
[Guest]: So they say, we don't get any funds, you know, all the funds are diverted towards Saurashtra

00:24:07.200 --> 00:24:08.200
[Guest]: and Kutch.

00:24:08.200 --> 00:24:12.280
[Guest]: So they started a movement incidentally, Bal Thackeray's father was also a big part of

00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:17.040
[Guest]: that movement and they started and then the Congress in those days who did not have any

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:21.240
[Guest]: competition, began to lose a lot of votes, you know, I mean, they began to lose a lot

00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:27.440
[Guest]: of seats and it went to all Chutput parties, I would say, you know, I mean, like Sayukta

00:24:27.440 --> 00:24:30.960
[Guest]: Maharashtra Movement Party and Communist Party and things like that.

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:34.560
[Guest]: They were not really very strong parties, but still people prefer to vote against the

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:35.560
[Guest]: Congress.

00:24:35.560 --> 00:24:40.440
[Guest]: So Nehru got unnerved and then he gave in to Chavan's exhortation, said, Muraji said

00:24:40.440 --> 00:24:43.960
[Guest]: that if you are splitting Bombay state, you know, we want Bombay as our state capital

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:47.440
[Guest]: because we are responsible for building it up the way it is.

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:51.240
[Guest]: But then Nehru conceded and gave Bombay to Maharashtra.

00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:56.160
[Guest]: But once Bombay came to Maharashtra, local Maharashtrians discovered that they still

00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:58.600
[Guest]: did not have rights in their own state capital.

00:24:58.600 --> 00:25:02.200
[Guest]: They were still second class citizens because this was full of South Indians.

00:25:02.200 --> 00:25:06.240
[Guest]: If you go and look up the Bombay Municipal Corporation, the list of mayors up to the

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:12.240
[Guest]: 50s and the 60s are all South Indians, Keralites, Tamilians, Kannadigas or Parsis, etc.

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:13.240
[Guest]: There's not a single Maharashtrian.

00:25:13.240 --> 00:25:17.120
[Guest]: Gujaratis are also mayors, but not a single Maharashtrian.

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:21.880
[Guest]: And then, you know, in South Bombay, in areas like Girgaon and all those kind of places,

00:25:21.880 --> 00:25:26.360
[Guest]: there was a major redevelopment, the kind that is taking place in Muhammad Ali Road,

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:28.800
[Guest]: which is under the Syedna, he's redeveloping the area.

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:33.760
[Guest]: So Maharashtra government had taken a redevelopment and during that redevelopment, much of the

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:38.000
[Guest]: housing went to either the South Indians or the rich Gujaratis.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.160
[Guest]: Nothing came to Maharashtrians.

00:25:39.160 --> 00:25:42.160
[Guest]: And this is what bothered Thackeray quite a lot.

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:47.120
[Guest]: You know, and that is how he set up the Shiv Sena saying that if there are jobs going in

00:25:47.120 --> 00:25:51.840
[Guest]: Bombay and if there are, he was basically a Bombay based party at that point of time.

00:25:51.840 --> 00:25:56.400
[Guest]: And if there is a housing redevelopment, houses have to go to Maharashtrians and jobs have

00:25:56.400 --> 00:25:57.440
[Guest]: to go to Maharashtrians.

00:25:57.440 --> 00:26:03.160
[Guest]: And that is how the whole, what do you say, it's still cosmopolitan, but it shifted its

00:26:03.160 --> 00:26:05.120
[Guest]: focus towards Maharashtrians after that.

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:09.400
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact, your book, Maharashtra Maximus does a very good job of sort of delineating

00:26:09.400 --> 00:26:12.760
[Amit Varma]: the second fault line, the Maharashtrians versus Gujaratis fault line.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:17.480
[Amit Varma]: Like as you point out, you know, before independence, the British had set up the BMC and you could

00:26:17.480 --> 00:26:19.480
[Amit Varma]: only vote if you were a taxpayer.

00:26:19.480 --> 00:26:23.960
[Amit Varma]: So the majority of the taxpayers were Gujaratis, Parsis, Boras, Sindhis, because the Maharashtrians

00:26:23.960 --> 00:26:29.200
[Amit Varma]: happened to be mostly the migrant labor brought in to work in the mills and so on and so forth.

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:33.720
[Amit Varma]: And then even after independence, when you have universal franchise, but still, you know,

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:38.800
[Amit Varma]: as a sort of legacy of the past, your corporators and all that are Gujaratis, Parsis, Boras

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:44.000
[Amit Varma]: and Sindhis, but your bureaucrats are all Tamil and you know, they are running the administration.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.880
[Amit Varma]: And this is, as you point out, what led to the Samyukta Maharashtra movement coming up.

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:52.160
[Amit Varma]: I was struck by this very amusing anecdote, which gave me a sense of how shrill the rhetoric

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:58.160
[Amit Varma]: got, where when Murarji was Chief Minister, like at one point to just give context to

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:02.200
[Amit Varma]: this, you say, I'll quote from your book, quote, the turning point in the agitation

00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:06.840
[Amit Varma]: came when he ordered, he being Murarji, ordered the police to fire on a protesting mob at

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Flora Fountain, which resulted in the martyring of a hundred and six protesters, a fact that

00:27:11.840 --> 00:27:15.200
[Amit Varma]: has not yet been forgotten by the local populace, stop quote.

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:18.720
[Amit Varma]: And obviously this spilled out in the streets and Maharashtrian leaders, you write, who

00:27:18.720 --> 00:27:23.560
[Amit Varma]: were stalwarts of the Samyukta Maharashtra movement, coined this beautiful slogan, Mumbai

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:27.200
[Amit Varma]: aahi aamchi, nahi konachi bappachi.

00:27:27.200 --> 00:27:28.760
[Guest]: It doesn't belong to anybody's father.

00:27:28.760 --> 00:27:29.760
[Amit Varma]: It belongs to us.

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:30.760
[Amit Varma]: It belongs to us.

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:32.880
[Guest]: No, it's nobody's father's property.

00:27:32.880 --> 00:27:35.320
[Guest]: And Murarji got really very angry with that.

00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:39.880
[Guest]: You know, rural Marathi is sometimes very rustic and even Thakre used to speak a bit

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:40.880
[Guest]: like that.

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:44.560
[Guest]: He used to call it Thakri Bhaja, you know, very rough, very rude, very rustic, but they

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:47.640
[Guest]: probably don't mean anything with that.

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:50.400
[Guest]: So Murarji got a little angry about that.

00:27:50.400 --> 00:27:56.620
[Guest]: So he said, barah Mumbai tumchi, ata bhandi ghasan aamchi.

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:59.120
[Guest]: That means now you come and scrub our utensils.

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:03.640
[Guest]: What he meant to say is that we are the rich entrepreneurs and you are just domestic servants

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:04.680
[Guest]: in our house.

00:28:04.680 --> 00:28:06.520
[Guest]: So that is your place.

00:28:06.520 --> 00:28:10.120
[Guest]: And that is what really rattled the Samyukta Maharashtra movement, saying that, you know,

00:28:10.120 --> 00:28:15.160
[Guest]: I mean, in our own state, in our own city, you know, I mean, they are making us feel

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:19.200
[Guest]: as second class citizens and then they came out on the streets and Murarji was again,

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:20.760
[Guest]: you know, very hot tempered man.

00:28:20.760 --> 00:28:25.920
[Guest]: So he ordered a firing and those 106 people were martyred and the movement never looked

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:26.920
[Guest]: back after that.

00:28:26.920 --> 00:28:30.000
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they had to concede Bombay to Maharashtra.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:35.080
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I'm just thinking that if a chief minister today ordered a firing and 106 people

00:28:35.080 --> 00:28:38.920
[Amit Varma]: died in Flora Fountain, I mean, it's almost unthinkable.

00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:43.320
[Amit Varma]: And so one can sort of imagine how deep the wounds went.

00:28:43.320 --> 00:28:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And you also, you sort of point out in your book about how there were all these different

00:28:46.720 --> 00:28:50.960
[Amit Varma]: little groupings which were coming up, fighting for the cause of the Marathi people like the

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:55.280
[Amit Varma]: Samyukta Maharashtra movement and so on and so forth.

00:28:55.280 --> 00:29:00.360
[Amit Varma]: But what made Bal Thackeray Shiv Sena stand out was his oratory and his ability to draw

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:01.360
[Guest]: the crowds.

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:02.360
[Guest]: Yes.

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:06.560
[Guest]: You know, if you have read my book on Bal Thackeray, I have insisted that, you know,

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:10.640
[Guest]: Bal Thackeray is a creature of the Congress, you know, because the Congress leaders also

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:15.080
[Guest]: were rebelling against this, you know, domination of South Indians, domination of Gujaratis,

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:16.080
[Guest]: etc.

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:18.080
[Guest]: They wanted a state for themselves.

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:22.480
[Guest]: And much of what Bal Thackeray said later, you know, speak Marathi in BMC, it did not

00:29:22.480 --> 00:29:25.280
[Guest]: come from Shiv Sena or Bal Thackeray.

00:29:25.280 --> 00:29:26.680
[Guest]: It came from the Congress leaders.

00:29:26.680 --> 00:29:27.920
[Guest]: It came from George Fernandez.

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:29.360
[Guest]: It came from Rinal Gore.

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:33.160
[Guest]: It didn't come from Bal Thackeray because there was this sub-nationalism even in the

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:35.000
[Guest]: Congress leaders.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.880
[Guest]: But they were these Gandhi topiwallas, they were these khadi clad leaders and they could

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:43.040
[Guest]: hardly descend on the streets and they could hardly say that, you know, throughout the

00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:44.040
[Guest]: South Indians.

00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:48.960
[Guest]: Now, you know, I mean, when the Shiv Sena came to power in 1995, Bal Thackeray in his

00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:53.400
[Guest]: first address said that, you know, I mean, we will deny ration cards to North Indians,

00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:54.400
[Guest]: migrating North Indians.

00:29:54.400 --> 00:29:57.600
[Guest]: By that time, North Indians were migrating in hoards to Mumbai.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:30:03.040
[Guest]: But the first claim like that was made by a Sayukta Maharashtra movement legislator

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:07.380
[Guest]: in the assembly saying that we should deny ration cards to South Indians.

00:30:07.380 --> 00:30:08.380
[Guest]: We should not allow them.

00:30:08.380 --> 00:30:12.280
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they are consuming our water, they are consuming our natural resources,

00:30:12.280 --> 00:30:13.280
[Guest]: etc.

00:30:13.280 --> 00:30:14.880
[Guest]: So Bal Thackeray only copied those ideas.

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:18.880
[Guest]: However, the Congress could not openly come out and say these kind of things.

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:22.440
[Guest]: So they kind of, you know, I mean, set up Bal Thackeray.

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:27.000
[Guest]: And in those days in the 70s, Shiv Sena used to be known as Vasanth Sena.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:30.840
[Guest]: After Vasanth Rao Naik, who was the chief minister and Vasanth Dada Patil, who was the

00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:33.320
[Guest]: Maharashtra Pradesh Congress president.

00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:39.000
[Guest]: So it was a clear indication that, you know, they are the ones who are funding and fueling,

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:42.880
[Guest]: you know, Bal Thackeray's sub-nationalism and his regionalism.

00:30:42.880 --> 00:30:47.280
[Guest]: And at that point of time, there was a sharp divide between Maharashtrians on one side,

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:50.880
[Guest]: South Indians, of course, because they were white collar workers, but they were more easily

00:30:50.880 --> 00:30:51.880
[Guest]: surmountable.

00:30:51.880 --> 00:30:56.400
[Guest]: And the Gujaratis who were the moneybags and the Congress needed the moneybags for themselves,

00:30:56.400 --> 00:31:01.400
[Guest]: you know, so they had to be very careful and they had to do it in a very diplomatic fashion.

00:31:01.400 --> 00:31:03.240
[Guest]: And Bal Thackeray was their answer to that.

00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And the tactical element of this is very interesting, because again, another thing people might

00:31:07.240 --> 00:31:11.640
[Amit Varma]: not realize today, where the communists have pretty much been decimated everywhere.

00:31:11.640 --> 00:31:14.320
[Amit Varma]: But in those days, in the 50s and 60s, the communists were very big.

00:31:14.320 --> 00:31:18.920
[Amit Varma]: They were the, you know, the biggest threat in a sense, in a local sense to the Congress.

00:31:18.920 --> 00:31:21.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, they had all the mill workers with them and all that.

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:26.080
[Amit Varma]: So tactically, it made total sense for the Congress to have their so-called D-team, you

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:31.560
[Amit Varma]: know, the Vasanth Sena and then let these guys fight the communists while they can just

00:31:31.560 --> 00:31:33.760
[Amit Varma]: sit back and, you know, sort of be the mature party.

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:38.320
[Amit Varma]: Like there's a political concept I think of in this regard, which is the Overton window.

00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:44.680
[Amit Varma]: So the Overton window basically is, it's sort of this space within which this linear space

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:48.600
[Amit Varma]: within which there is a window, which constitutes acceptable discourse.

00:31:48.600 --> 00:31:49.600
[Amit Varma]: Right?

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:53.760
[Amit Varma]: So for example, if it is drawn along the line of freedom, at one extreme, you have complete

00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:57.140
[Amit Varma]: freedom at the other extreme, you have complete authoritarianism.

00:31:57.140 --> 00:31:59.840
[Amit Varma]: And in between, there's a window of what the discourse is.

00:31:59.840 --> 00:32:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And the Overton window can shift where if one party makes a lot of noise, say in terms

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:09.440
[Amit Varma]: of total freedom, then people who would, the window shifts in that direction.

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:13.800
[Amit Varma]: So people who would otherwise not have been acceptable in the discourse suddenly seem

00:32:13.800 --> 00:32:14.800
[Amit Varma]: moderate.

00:32:14.800 --> 00:32:18.880
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just sort of thinking aloud, tell me if you agree with this, that what this

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:24.360
[Amit Varma]: also made the Congress, it made the Congress look more mature and more reasonable and almost

00:32:24.360 --> 00:32:28.560
[Amit Varma]: like the adults in the room, because you have these two crazies on either side.

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:30.920
[Guest]: Yes, and that is what their intention was.

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:34.960
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they did not want to soil their hands, you know, by getting into this

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:38.720
[Guest]: whole thing and becoming parochial and pushing out other people.

00:32:38.720 --> 00:32:42.520
[Guest]: The Constitution allows freedom of movement anywhere in the country and the Congress,

00:32:42.520 --> 00:32:47.560
[Guest]: you know, just coming out freshly out of freedom, just 20 years into freedom, they just really

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:49.280
[Guest]: could not do this kind of a thing.

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:53.800
[Guest]: So they set up this maverick, you know, I mean, who was, but how did he get away?

00:32:53.800 --> 00:32:58.360
[Guest]: Because you know, there's also a murder case, they murdered a communist leader in Lalbagh.

00:32:58.360 --> 00:33:02.080
[Guest]: And then a Shiv Sena man contested that seat, you know, and he became the first legislator

00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:04.080
[Guest]: in the Maharashtra Assembly.

00:33:04.080 --> 00:33:06.400
[Guest]: How did the Shiv Sena and Bal Thackeray get away with it?

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:10.000
[Guest]: You know, I mean, unless they had the sanction of the authorities, unless the government

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.480
[Guest]: was protecting, you know, I mean, he could not have got away with it.

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:13.480
[Guest]: The case is still in court.

00:33:13.480 --> 00:33:14.480
[Guest]: It is 40, 50 years.

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:15.480
[Unknown]: This was Dange.

00:33:15.480 --> 00:33:16.480
[Amit Varma]: No, Desai, Krishna Desai.

00:33:16.480 --> 00:33:26.400
[Guest]: Dange was another person with whom Bal Thackeray, although he was a communist, and Bal Thackeray

00:33:26.400 --> 00:33:29.400
[Guest]: was a, what do you say, sharp regionalist.

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:36.000
[Guest]: Dange and Bal Thackeray came together briefly, maybe one or a couple of meetings in Lalbagh.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:39.080
[Guest]: And then Thackeray never liked to concede second place to anybody.

00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:43.640
[Guest]: And Dange also had a great oratory, not in Thackeray's style, but he had a great oratory

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:48.280
[Guest]: with which the mill workers reacted to and listened to and they resonated with it.

00:33:48.280 --> 00:33:52.200
[Guest]: So Thackeray did not like the fact that Dange was overshadowing him, you know.

00:33:52.200 --> 00:33:54.240
[Guest]: So he promptly dropped that alliance with Dange.

00:33:54.240 --> 00:33:57.720
[Amit Varma]: No, and I remember you mentioned this part in your book that, you know, Thackeray calls

00:33:57.720 --> 00:34:01.480
[Amit Varma]: him and they give a speech and Dange speaks first.

00:34:01.480 --> 00:34:04.400
[Unknown]: And he's so reasonable and yet he gets a crowd with him.

00:34:04.400 --> 00:34:08.480
[Unknown]: Thackeray is, of course, you know, a rabble rouser and Thackeray immediately then never

00:34:08.480 --> 00:34:09.480
[Amit Varma]: asked.

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:13.280
[Amit Varma]: And the person accused of the Desai murder eventually became a minister in the 95th cabinet.

00:34:13.280 --> 00:34:14.280
[Guest]: Yes, yes, yes.

00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:19.040
[Guest]: He became a minister and he was not brought to book, you know, I mean, so it could not

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:24.800
[Guest]: have happened without the complicit sanction of the rulers at that time and the rulers

00:34:24.800 --> 00:34:27.040
[Amit Varma]: were only the Congress, you know.

00:34:27.040 --> 00:34:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And in your book on Thackeray, Hindu Raza Samrat, you've got these very evocative early

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:37.520
[Amit Varma]: sections that give us a glimpse into Thackeray's early resentments, like when he worked at

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:39.520
[Unknown]: the Free Press Journal, for example, R.K.

00:34:39.520 --> 00:34:44.720
[Amit Varma]: Lakshman was one of his colleagues and everybody else, all the senior management, the editors

00:34:44.720 --> 00:34:49.600
[Unknown]: and all that was South India and they kept referring Lakshman's cartoons to his and he

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:55.500
[Amit Varma]: felt that that was discrimination and his cartoons have been described by various people

00:34:55.500 --> 00:34:58.640
[Amit Varma]: as being extremely crude and not quite in the Lakshman class.

00:34:58.640 --> 00:35:02.760
[Amit Varma]: But he took that resentment with him almost like a generation earlier and I don't mean

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:07.920
[Amit Varma]: to imply an equivalence, but almost as if, you know, 50 years before that, you know,

00:35:07.920 --> 00:35:13.300
[Amit Varma]: Hitler took the knocks he got at art school from the Jews and so on and carried that resentment

00:35:13.300 --> 00:35:15.080
[Amit Varma]: all the way through.

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:19.240
[Amit Varma]: My question is, you've known Thackeray pretty well personally as well.

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:25.160
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, one can say that this was a genuine ideology, that he really felt strongly

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:28.840
[Unknown]: about this, that we Marathis must have our place and he was really committed to that

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:30.420
[Amit Varma]: sub-nationalism.

00:35:30.420 --> 00:35:34.280
[Amit Varma]: But then as you also point out, there are so many contradictions in his actions and

00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:38.520
[Amit Varma]: his targets keep shifting according to what is tactically feasible at different points

00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:43.400
[Amit Varma]: in time from South Indians to Muslims to North Indians later and so on.

00:35:43.400 --> 00:35:48.920
[Amit Varma]: So was he a man who had firm beliefs of any kind and ideology of some sort or was he a

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:54.440
[Amit Varma]: political tactician who wanted to be a politician and then just picked whatever niche was most

00:35:54.440 --> 00:35:55.920
[Guest]: promising at a given point in time?

00:35:55.920 --> 00:36:00.200
[Guest]: No, I think he was a political tactician, you know, he was not committed to any ideology.

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:04.400
[Guest]: Otherwise, he would not have aligned with the Muslim League.

00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:11.120
[Guest]: He would not have called for a school or a hospital on the disputed site in Ayodhya,

00:36:11.120 --> 00:36:17.240
[Guest]: which he did after participating in the riots post the demolition of the Babri Masjid.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:20.620
[Guest]: He then later called for a school or a hospital when he realized that the Muslims were voting

00:36:20.620 --> 00:36:23.680
[Guest]: for him because Muslims had extended an olive branch.

00:36:23.680 --> 00:36:28.260
[Guest]: And you know, I have always insisted that his only ideology was himself.

00:36:28.260 --> 00:36:30.240
[Guest]: He did believe in the Marathi Manus.

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:34.520
[Guest]: He did want to get something for them, but there again, if you notice, you know, the

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:39.040
[Guest]: generational change that has happened in the Shiv Sena, he worked with lumpens.

00:36:39.040 --> 00:36:43.320
[Guest]: You know, he wanted an army, you know, like one call to the army and, you know, they are

00:36:43.320 --> 00:36:45.960
[Guest]: all in the streets, they are flooding the streets and they are causing problems, you

00:36:45.960 --> 00:36:48.400
[Guest]: know, they're causing riots, etc.

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:53.680
[Guest]: So he had an interest in keeping them slightly undereducated, you know, I mean, people who

00:36:53.680 --> 00:36:55.280
[Guest]: will not turn around and ask questions.

00:36:55.280 --> 00:37:00.360
[Guest]: Like, you know, a friend of mine told me that when you join the NDA, they of course, they

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:05.240
[Guest]: fail you if you get three out of ten, but they also fail you if you get eight out of

00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:06.240
[Guest]: ten.

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:07.760
[Guest]: So it's between four and seven.

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:11.440
[Guest]: Four and seven, because they don't want you to be too intelligent and ask questions and

00:37:11.440 --> 00:37:13.360
[Guest]: question your commanding officers.

00:37:13.360 --> 00:37:15.960
[Guest]: So that is what was with Bal Thackeray.

00:37:15.960 --> 00:37:19.160
[Guest]: He did not want too educated and too questioning people, you know.

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:23.560
[Guest]: So yes, you know, I mean, moderately educated and then, you know, like with his Lokadikar

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:28.000
[Guest]: Samiti and like with his trade unions, he will come to know that there are jobs opening

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.040
[Guest]: up in Air India or Mazgaon docks and, you know, they will be very happy.

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:36.560
[Guest]: Balasaheb got us a job as fitter, loader, turner in all these places.

00:37:36.560 --> 00:37:40.880
[Guest]: But they never had any ambition beyond that, you know, I mean, it is only the second generation

00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:45.200
[Guest]: which has woken up and realized that they were not qualified, you know, I mean, their

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:47.000
[Guest]: children were not qualified, etc.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:48.600
[Guest]: Or they were not qualified.

00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:53.240
[Guest]: And so they started to send their children to better schools, wanted them to become graduates,

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:56.560
[Guest]: wanted them to speak English and not restrict themselves to Marathi.

00:37:56.560 --> 00:38:01.680
[Guest]: I have quoted, you know, someone in my book, Arun Tikkarkar, who was the editor of Lok

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:02.680
[Guest]: Satta.

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:08.600
[Guest]: So he said, Maharashtrian society suffered a generational setback thrice in the past

00:38:08.600 --> 00:38:09.600
[Guest]: few centuries.

00:38:09.600 --> 00:38:13.960
[Guest]: One was this war of Panipat, which the Peshwas lost, the Marathas lost.

00:38:13.960 --> 00:38:15.800
[Guest]: It took them 25 years to come back.

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:19.280
[Guest]: Second was Mahatma Gandhi's assassination by Nathuram Godse.

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:21.920
[Guest]: People did not trust Maharashtrians for a long time after that.

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:25.800
[Guest]: There were very few Maharashtrians in Nehru's cabinet or in Indira Gandhi's cabinet, etc.

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:27.440
[Guest]: They didn't trust Maharashtrians.

00:38:27.440 --> 00:38:32.240
[Guest]: And the third was when Bal Thackeray set up the Shiv Sena, you know, because outside of

00:38:32.240 --> 00:38:36.160
[Guest]: Maharashtra, everybody got the picture of Maharashtrians as, you know, I mean, wicked,

00:38:36.160 --> 00:38:40.400
[Guest]: evil, writers, you know, I mean, they are terrible, you know, I mean, they kill you,

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:44.680
[Guest]: you know, I mean, they don't allow you to seek jobs in the state and things like that,

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:49.000
[Guest]: in which the middle class Maharashtrians hated that picture.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:51.440
[Guest]: They hated that picture because they knew that they were not like that.

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:55.280
[Guest]: So there was one time when only the lumpens were supporting Bal Thackeray.

00:38:55.280 --> 00:38:58.640
[Guest]: But then when Uddhav Thackeray took over the thing, he realized what had happened and he

00:38:58.640 --> 00:39:03.200
[Guest]: wanted a better class of Maharashtrians to be supporting the Shiv Sena, to be representing

00:39:03.200 --> 00:39:07.560
[Guest]: the Shiv Sena, which is why this change has taken place, you know, I mean, and also the

00:39:07.560 --> 00:39:11.680
[Guest]: government that we have got, it is essentially because the Shiv Sena has stopped being the

00:39:11.680 --> 00:39:15.960
[Guest]: kind of violent party, you know, okay, fine, it is saying Hindutva, it is asking for the

00:39:15.960 --> 00:39:19.240
[Guest]: Ram temple, but they have managed to keep that on the back burner.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:22.560
[Guest]: And they managed to form a government essentially because they are nonviolent and they believe

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:23.560
[Guest]: in the constitution.

00:39:23.560 --> 00:39:27.360
[Guest]: Bal Thackeray never believed in the constitution or in nonviolence.

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:32.680
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact, another thing I realized while reading your book is the key shifts

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:37.520
[Amit Varma]: in the Shiv Sena, like we see that when it starts, a lot of the people who are with Thackeray

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:41.920
[Amit Varma]: are actually educated people who are reading because he started this magazine called Marmik,

00:39:41.920 --> 00:39:46.880
[Amit Varma]: as you point out, and they're all educated middle class Maharashtrians who are sort of

00:39:46.880 --> 00:39:47.880
[Amit Varma]: with the movement.

00:39:47.880 --> 00:39:51.640
[Amit Varma]: And then he goes completely the lumpen way and the rowdies sort of take over the party

00:39:51.640 --> 00:39:55.280
[Unknown]: and that's happening through the 70s into the late 70s.

00:39:55.280 --> 00:40:01.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that earlier the thinking rationalist educated middle class kind of goes away from

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:03.340
[Amit Varma]: him and it becomes a party of lumpens.

00:40:03.340 --> 00:40:06.960
[Amit Varma]: And you've got this very evocative chapter in your book called Marathi Manus, which in

00:40:06.960 --> 00:40:08.840
[Amit Varma]: fact I first read as a Kindle single.

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:10.800
[Unknown]: It was I think released on its own.

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:13.520
[Amit Varma]: And it's also there on juggernaut on its own, I think.

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:15.520
[Amit Varma]: And I'll link that from the show notes.

00:40:15.520 --> 00:40:21.720
[Amit Varma]: And that describes it very evocatively how, because he would get these menial jobs for

00:40:21.720 --> 00:40:27.220
[Amit Varma]: his Shiv Sena foot soldiers through the use of force and all that, that there'll be factory

00:40:27.220 --> 00:40:32.480
[Amit Varma]: watchmen and there'll be, you know, jobs of that sort, that there wasn't a stress on education

00:40:32.480 --> 00:40:33.700
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:38.680
[Amit Varma]: And because of that, an entire generation lost those opportunities and they just kind

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:39.680
[Amit Varma]: of went forever.

00:40:39.680 --> 00:40:44.040
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that in that particular case, normally politicians don't

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:48.640
[Amit Varma]: walk the talk, but in that particular case, even his, the kids of his own family, Uddhav

00:40:48.640 --> 00:40:52.360
[Guest]: and Raj didn't really have a great education in the sense they went.

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:53.360
[Guest]: No, they didn't.

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:55.000
[Guest]: That is one thing you have to give credit to Thackeray.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.920
[Guest]: You know, I mean, he imposed me Marathi and he imposed, you know, I'm in Marathi medium.

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:01.480
[Guest]: So he sent his children to those kinds of schools.

00:41:01.480 --> 00:41:03.320
[Guest]: Today they feel handicapped.

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:06.440
[Guest]: They feel handicapped, which is why they have sent their children to Bombay's courtesans

00:41:06.440 --> 00:41:08.080
[Guest]: and Xavier's and things like that.

00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:12.160
[Guest]: And I think Rashmi and Uddhav Thackeray are very proud of Aditya Thackeray that he's able

00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:13.160
[Guest]: to hold his own.

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:14.160
[Guest]: He's part of the Pathri crowd.

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:17.680
[Guest]: He's part of the bold and beautiful, which they were never able to do.

00:41:17.680 --> 00:41:22.040
[Guest]: You know, I mean, because not only that, you know, I mean, Uddhav and Raj were not really

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:28.280
[Guest]: educated in that sense, but, but, you know, I mean, they were also seen as such, you know,

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:31.520
[Guest]: I mean, in the sense, you know, these are not the kind of people we want to associate

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:34.320
[Guest]: with, because they are violent, they beat up people.

00:41:34.320 --> 00:41:37.280
[Guest]: And even, even middle class Maharashtrians didn't want to do it.

00:41:37.280 --> 00:41:41.000
[Guest]: Forget about North Indians and South Indians and other people, they didn't want to do it.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:44.200
[Guest]: So it has been a conscious shift in the Shiv Sena.

00:41:44.200 --> 00:41:49.800
[Guest]: And in that chapter, which you just quoted, I have a story about this person who's now

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:53.240
[Guest]: a very top ranking PR person.

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:58.440
[Guest]: And he was living in Lalbagh and his mother was in, was teaching English in a government

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:01.440
[Guest]: school, in a government or a municipal school.

00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:05.960
[Guest]: But, you know, long before Thackeray's policy of Me Marathi, she wanted her children to

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:07.840
[Guest]: learn the mother tongue.

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:13.920
[Guest]: So she put her children into Marathi medium schools, initially, you know, primary, etc.

00:42:13.920 --> 00:42:17.400
[Guest]: But whenever they wanted to read English books, you know, she always went to the library and

00:42:17.400 --> 00:42:21.720
[Guest]: got them, you know, so she got them Shakespeare, she got them Banerjee, etc.

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:26.040
[Guest]: And as these children grew up, they began more interested in reading English literature,

00:42:26.040 --> 00:42:27.040
[Guest]: etc.

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:31.280
[Guest]: And then they began to question and Lalbagh was really right in the heart of the Shiv

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:33.600
[Guest]: Sena fortress, you know.

00:42:33.600 --> 00:42:39.240
[Guest]: So this particular person began to question Thackeray's parochial policies and he got

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:43.200
[Guest]: beaten up, right, royally by all the Shiv Sena supporters, etc.

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:46.880
[Guest]: Every time he used to get beaten up whenever he used to ask questions, but then he got

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:47.880
[Guest]: a job.

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:50.920
[Guest]: First he became a journalist, then he moved into PR.

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:55.920
[Guest]: And now he lives in a huge flat and he facing the sea.

00:42:55.920 --> 00:42:59.560
[Guest]: And he has about two or three cars parked in his basement, etc.

00:42:59.560 --> 00:43:03.200
[Guest]: And then he told me that, you know, I mean, I'm still friends with those people that I

00:43:03.200 --> 00:43:04.360
[Guest]: grew up with.

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:08.120
[Guest]: And then I invite them home and then they come and then they look at my cars and then

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:12.120
[Guest]: they look at my house and they look at the sea facing window, etc.

00:43:12.120 --> 00:43:13.400
[Guest]: And they don't say anything.

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:17.220
[Guest]: And even I don't say anything, although I want to tell them, I tell you so.

00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:22.560
[Guest]: And I want to tell them that, you know, around the time when you were lending your muscle

00:43:22.560 --> 00:43:27.720
[Guest]: to Bal Thackeray, I was sitting in the libraries of Mumbai reading Shakespeare in Burnet Shaw.

00:43:27.720 --> 00:43:28.880
[Guest]: And getting mocked for it.

00:43:28.880 --> 00:43:29.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:33.160
[Guest]: Which is why I'm here and you are where you are, you know, I mean, so that, that's

00:43:33.160 --> 00:43:37.120
[Guest]: that difference has been understood by the second generation of Shiv Senik.

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:38.480
[Guest]: So they don't want that.

00:43:38.480 --> 00:43:41.200
[Guest]: And if you remember, I don't know whether you were in Bombay that time.

00:43:41.200 --> 00:43:44.520
[Guest]: There was a time, you know, when the Shiv Seniks used to go to all these convent schools,

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:48.240
[Guest]: you know, St. Anne's, Don Bosco, etc.

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:51.720
[Guest]: And they used to beat up the fathers and the nuns, etc., because they wanted their children

00:43:51.720 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest]: to be admitted to those schools.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:57.240
[Guest]: And these missionary schools, you know, they have a very strict thing, you know, I mean,

00:43:57.240 --> 00:44:00.920
[Guest]: and they also put a lot of weightage on their parents.

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:04.240
[Guest]: Are your parents educated, are your parents speaking English, you know, I mean, are they

00:44:04.240 --> 00:44:05.840
[Guest]: capable of doing your homework?

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:07.320
[Guest]: I mean, helping you do your homework, etc.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:08.320
[Amit Varma]: Do they beat up the teachers?

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:11.760
[Guest]: Yeah, because you are not admitting, you're not admitting, you know, I mean, that kind

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:12.840
[Guest]: of a thing.

00:44:12.840 --> 00:44:16.840
[Guest]: And then the Archdiocese, you know, they passed a law saying that we are not going to listen

00:44:16.840 --> 00:44:18.120
[Guest]: to politicians.

00:44:18.120 --> 00:44:21.960
[Guest]: I mean, we are not going to admit politician children just because they are, you know,

00:44:21.960 --> 00:44:25.120
[Guest]: I mean, they are politicians' children, they have to come here on merit.

00:44:25.120 --> 00:44:27.760
[Guest]: You know, the parents have to come and they have to answer the same questions.

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:31.080
[Guest]: And when they realize that they're not getting admission in these schools, then they shifted

00:44:31.080 --> 00:44:34.880
[Guest]: to certain other schools like, you know, Bombay Scottish, which doesn't have that kind of

00:44:34.880 --> 00:44:38.880
[Guest]: a rule, you know, it is not run by missionaries, etc., you know, American International, they

00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:42.440
[Guest]: send their children to those schools, but they definitely got them a proper education.

00:44:42.440 --> 00:44:43.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that you also talk about like the second interesting shift that happens,

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:51.200
[Amit Varma]: like one is, of course, a shift to the Shiv Sena in the late 70s becoming this lumpen

00:44:51.200 --> 00:44:52.440
[Amit Varma]: party.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:57.320
[Amit Varma]: And the other shift is after they come to power in 95, they get drunk on power and your

00:44:57.320 --> 00:45:02.200
[Amit Varma]: common Shiv Sena foot soldiers are doing extortions and taking money from common people.

00:45:02.200 --> 00:45:06.120
[Amit Varma]: At one point, you write in your book that people stopped buying cars or doing any kind

00:45:06.120 --> 00:45:07.920
[Guest]: of conspicuous consumption.

00:45:07.920 --> 00:45:08.920
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And then that changed.

00:45:10.320 --> 00:45:14.640
[Guest]: Yeah, but that essentially changed because people reacted to that.

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:18.000
[Guest]: This was between 96 and 98.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:23.040
[Guest]: Even people like doctors and lawyers and professionals like that, they were dressing down, they would

00:45:23.040 --> 00:45:27.680
[Guest]: probably drive in a Maruti 800 instead of a Mercedes Benz and things like that, because

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:31.480
[Guest]: they knew that they were under the focus of all the shakha pramukhs, etc.

00:45:31.480 --> 00:45:39.760
[Guest]: You know, it got so bad because the Shiv Sena has got this labor unions in five star hotels,

00:45:39.760 --> 00:45:41.240
[Guest]: in hospitals also.

00:45:41.240 --> 00:45:46.000
[Guest]: So even if a heart patient was admitted to hospital and he went in for heart surgery,

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:52.080
[Guest]: and after that, the doctor would get an extortionist call, and even the patient would get an extortionist

00:45:52.080 --> 00:45:53.080
[Guest]: call.

00:45:53.080 --> 00:45:55.720
[Guest]: They'd say, we know that you paid so many lakhs for this operation.

00:45:55.720 --> 00:45:59.200
[Guest]: And then they would tell the doctor that we know that you earn so many lakhs, so you can

00:45:59.200 --> 00:46:00.840
[Guest]: afford to pay us this much, etc.

00:46:00.840 --> 00:46:03.120
[Guest]: It became really, really, very bad.

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:06.360
[Guest]: And then it came to businessmen also, you know, I mean, these businessmen who had wanted

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:08.400
[Guest]: to support the Shiv Sena, etc.

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:13.760
[Guest]: So at that point of time, I think it was in 98, that they all got together and they held

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:15.400
[Guest]: a meeting at Chowpatty.

00:46:15.400 --> 00:46:16.960
[Guest]: And then they said, enough is enough.

00:46:16.960 --> 00:46:20.200
[Guest]: We are not going to stand this nonsense.

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:23.240
[Guest]: And they got a lot of support from the police commissioner at that time, etc.

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:26.880
[Guest]: Because even the police commissioner was sick and tired of all those extortionist calls

00:46:26.880 --> 00:46:29.680
[Guest]: and extortionist complaints and things like that.

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:33.600
[Guest]: So they got together and they said, we are not going to pay you a single Naya Paisa.

00:46:33.600 --> 00:46:37.280
[Guest]: Not only that, you know, I mean, businessmen going to Thackeray's house, you know, in posh

00:46:37.280 --> 00:46:41.520
[Guest]: cars would have to leave the keys there and come back without their cars, you know, I

00:46:41.520 --> 00:46:45.120
[Guest]: mean, so they would always go there in taxis.

00:46:45.120 --> 00:46:47.920
[Guest]: And you never knew, you know, there would be something like, you know, Thackeray is

00:46:47.920 --> 00:46:48.920
[Guest]: passing by someplace.

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:52.520
[Guest]: He's going to somebody's house and he sees this cake shop.

00:46:52.520 --> 00:46:57.040
[Guest]: He gets into the cake shop and he pays and he buys the cake to take it somewhere.

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:00.640
[Guest]: But after that, there would be a line of Shirseniks for days and days saying that we want this

00:47:00.640 --> 00:47:01.880
[Guest]: cake, we want this pastry, etc.

00:47:01.880 --> 00:47:04.560
[Guest]: And they would just walk away with it without anything, you know.

00:47:04.560 --> 00:47:07.200
[Guest]: I mean, so this kind of thing used to happen.

00:47:07.200 --> 00:47:09.400
[Guest]: And then they all got together and they said, enough is enough.

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:10.960
[Guest]: We are not going to pay you a single thing.

00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:13.520
[Guest]: And then Thackeray realized that he was in danger.

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:17.400
[Guest]: You know, I mean, if he lost the popular support and also he lost the support of people who

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:22.120
[Guest]: were donating to his party, I mean, proper donations to his party, then he would be in

00:47:22.120 --> 00:47:23.120
[Guest]: trouble.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:26.720
[Guest]: But having said that, I have to say that the Shiv Sena in Thackeray's time always had three

00:47:26.720 --> 00:47:28.480
[Guest]: kinds of Shirseniks.

00:47:28.480 --> 00:47:30.800
[Guest]: If I may say so, I mentioned it in my book also.

00:47:30.800 --> 00:47:33.140
[Guest]: One was the pure extortionist.

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:34.840
[Guest]: You know, he would go and he would extort.

00:47:34.840 --> 00:47:39.360
[Guest]: You know, somebody told me that every other political party, the political leader collects

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:43.040
[Guest]: money at the top and passes it down to the workers.

00:47:43.040 --> 00:47:46.640
[Guest]: Shiv Sena was the only party where the workers collected it from the bottom and passed it

00:47:46.640 --> 00:47:47.640
[Guest]: on to Thackeray.

00:47:47.640 --> 00:47:54.800
[Guest]: You know, but Thackeray, knowing that he could not walk into those shops himself and extort

00:47:54.800 --> 00:48:01.560
[Guest]: the money from them, he would pass on 20 percent of the collections to his Shiv Seniks, which

00:48:01.560 --> 00:48:07.920
[Guest]: is how they went from slums to chawls to flats to high rises to bungalows in some place or

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:08.920
[Guest]: dada.

00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:12.440
[Guest]: And they were very grateful to Thackeray because, you know, I mean, they said he shares it.

00:48:12.440 --> 00:48:15.400
[Guest]: He shares it with us because they know that they cannot extort in their own name.

00:48:15.400 --> 00:48:19.040
[Guest]: If they go and walk into a shop, nobody is going to pay them a second look.

00:48:19.040 --> 00:48:20.760
[Guest]: They're not going to give them a second look.

00:48:20.760 --> 00:48:22.920
[Guest]: So that was pure extortionism.

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:26.600
[Guest]: Then there were those who believed in violence along with extortion.

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:30.360
[Guest]: You know, if you resisted, then they would be violent.

00:48:30.360 --> 00:48:32.760
[Guest]: You know, I mean, and they were the more dangerous ones.

00:48:32.760 --> 00:48:37.680
[Guest]: And then there was a third one who was there only for Marathi asmita, Marathi pride, Marathi

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:38.680
[Guest]: ethos.

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:42.400
[Guest]: They are the ones who got really tired of this kind of a thing, extortion and extortion

00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:43.720
[Guest]: and violence.

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:50.440
[Guest]: And then, you know, Sharad Pawar broke the Congress in 1978 and he formed his own regional

00:48:50.440 --> 00:48:54.520
[Guest]: party and this Marathi ethos people all shifted to Sharad Pawar.

00:48:54.520 --> 00:48:58.080
[Guest]: So Thackeray lost a lot of his base at that point of time.

00:48:58.080 --> 00:49:03.680
[Guest]: The middle class intellectual Maharashtrian just shifted away from the Shiv Sena and went

00:49:03.680 --> 00:49:05.040
[Guest]: to the Congress.

00:49:05.040 --> 00:49:10.200
[Guest]: It would take another eight years for Sharad Pawar to rejoin Congress.

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:14.960
[Guest]: And then those people who didn't like Congress, they shifted base back to Shiv Sena.

00:49:14.960 --> 00:49:17.240
[Guest]: But by that time Thackeray had learnt his lesson.

00:49:17.240 --> 00:49:20.640
[Guest]: He knew that he could not be a pure extortionist and pure violent party.

00:49:20.640 --> 00:49:24.920
[Amit Varma]: No, I always think of political parties as sort of rival mafias, which are basically

00:49:24.920 --> 00:49:29.920
[Amit Varma]: just fighting for, you know, that period in time when you get the monopoly to power your

00:49:29.920 --> 00:49:30.920
[Amit Varma]: the state.

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:34.920
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, even if you steal public money, there's a subtle way to do it, which

00:49:34.920 --> 00:49:38.100
[Amit Varma]: is you form the government and you steal public money in so many ways.

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:42.800
[Amit Varma]: And there is the unsubtle crass way of doing it, which is, I guess, what Shiv Sena are

00:49:42.800 --> 00:49:45.280
[Amit Varma]: getting carried away and new to the business of politics.

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:50.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you could call them a nouveau mafia and they did for that period in time.

00:49:50.600 --> 00:49:51.960
[Amit Varma]: And then they also changed.

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:55.600
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of talk about Sharad Pawar a bit, because what is also very interesting

00:49:55.600 --> 00:49:59.600
[Amit Varma]: is that back in Thackeray's early days when he was in the Free Press Journal, Sharad Pawar

00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:00.600
[Guest]: used to hang out with him.

00:50:00.600 --> 00:50:05.360
[Guest]: Yes, Sharad Pawar used to hang out with him and he sapped in all the meetings and discussions

00:50:05.360 --> 00:50:07.920
[Guest]: that happened about the formation of the Shiv Sena.

00:50:07.920 --> 00:50:11.280
[Guest]: They used to sit somewhere in Elphinstone College.

00:50:11.280 --> 00:50:14.400
[Guest]: They used to hire a hall and sit in Elphinstone College.

00:50:14.400 --> 00:50:18.600
[Guest]: And there was, you know, I have mentioned in the book also that it is the industrialists

00:50:18.600 --> 00:50:23.700
[Guest]: of Bombay, along with the Congress politicians who had an interest in seeing the formation

00:50:23.700 --> 00:50:29.200
[Guest]: of the Shiv Sena so that they could use this kind of this army of lumpens, you know, I

00:50:29.200 --> 00:50:32.720
[Guest]: mean, to get what they couldn't through the usual routes.

00:50:32.720 --> 00:50:36.360
[Guest]: So Sharad Pawar was a youth Congress leader at that point of time.

00:50:36.360 --> 00:50:41.380
[Guest]: And although he may not admit it, I'm convinced, you know, I mean, that he was asked by some

00:50:41.380 --> 00:50:47.160
[Guest]: of the senior leaders, most probably the Chief Minister of Maharashtra at that time, Vasant

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:51.600
[Guest]: Rao Naik, you know, I mean, to sit in on those meetings and guide Thackeray into it.

00:50:51.600 --> 00:50:55.080
[Guest]: And there used to be a secretary of Ramkrishna Bajaj also who used to be sitting in on those

00:50:55.080 --> 00:50:56.080
[Guest]: meetings.

00:50:56.080 --> 00:51:04.480
[Guest]: So, you know, whether he had a real big role in the formation of the Shiv Sena, one cannot

00:51:04.480 --> 00:51:07.800
[Guest]: say, but he definitely sat there and he guided Thackeray.

00:51:07.800 --> 00:51:11.080
[Guest]: And they have been friends from that time, you know, I mean, everybody thinks that and

00:51:11.080 --> 00:51:14.760
[Guest]: I have mentioned, you know, that they are bitter political rivals, but in private life,

00:51:14.760 --> 00:51:16.640
[Amit Varma]: they are the best private friends.

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:20.520
[Amit Varma]: And there were at certain points, there was an overlap between the voters that they were

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:22.760
[Guest]: competing for, which is basically the Marathas.

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:23.760
[Guest]: Yes.

00:51:23.760 --> 00:51:29.640
[Guest]: Yes, Marathas in the sense, you know, I mean, Thackeray never really had, although he is

00:51:29.640 --> 00:51:34.760
[Guest]: based his party on Shivaji and, you know, on his name, he never really had Maratha Marathas

00:51:34.760 --> 00:51:35.760
[Guest]: in that sense.

00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:39.480
[Guest]: The Maratha vote was always with the Congress and later the NCP.

00:51:39.480 --> 00:51:43.200
[Guest]: And then it shifted to the BJP for certain political reasons.

00:51:43.200 --> 00:51:48.120
[Guest]: But a lot of, you know, the ones who believed in Marathi ethos, Marathi pride, and those

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:52.400
[Guest]: are the ones, you know, Sharad Pawar had been the chief minister in 78, then again in 88

00:51:52.400 --> 00:51:53.960
[Guest]: and then again in 90.

00:51:53.960 --> 00:51:58.200
[Guest]: And you know, he acquired the reputation of being a great administrator.

00:51:58.200 --> 00:52:01.480
[Guest]: And I wouldn't call him a visionary in the sense of Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru, but you

00:52:01.480 --> 00:52:03.840
[Guest]: know, he definitely was farsighted.

00:52:03.840 --> 00:52:06.240
[Guest]: He saw many things, you know.

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:13.000
[Guest]: So Maharashtrians prefer to, what do you say, identify with him rather than Bal Thackeray.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:20.400
[Guest]: You know, I mean, the more educated, the more soft spoken, the more, what do you say, knowledgeable.

00:52:20.400 --> 00:52:28.320
[Guest]: And Sharad Pawar is not very good at hype and beating his own, blowing his own trumpet.

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:33.360
[Guest]: But he has done a lot more for the people in the villages and rural areas and particularly

00:52:33.360 --> 00:52:34.860
[Guest]: his constituency.

00:52:34.860 --> 00:52:37.880
[Guest]: And people wanted to associate with him rather than Bal Thackeray.

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:41.840
[Guest]: Ajit Pawar, his nephew, once had said, you know, what has Bal Thackeray done for the

00:52:41.840 --> 00:52:42.840
[Guest]: people of Maharashtra?

00:52:42.840 --> 00:52:45.400
[Guest]: Has he set up a single educational institution?

00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:46.920
[Guest]: Has he set up a single sugar factory?

00:52:46.920 --> 00:52:50.560
[Guest]: Or has he set up anything else that is benefiting the common people of Maharashtra?

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:52.280
[Guest]: He's only been doing for himself, himself.

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:55.720
[Guest]: You know, he's been just, you know, he's been building a house, he's been building something

00:52:55.720 --> 00:52:59.560
[Guest]: and, you know, I mean, he's been doing nothing for the people, which is true also.

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:04.040
[Amit Varma]: In your book, you quote him as saying all he's done is built a house with 27 air conditioners.

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:08.000
[Guest]: Yes, there were 27 air conditioners in his house, you know.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:09.720
[Guest]: So, and which is really true.

00:53:09.720 --> 00:53:12.040
[Guest]: He never did anything for the Maharashtrian people.

00:53:12.040 --> 00:53:13.040
[Guest]: He never thought about it.

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:14.040
[Guest]: He didn't set up a hospital.

00:53:14.040 --> 00:53:15.040
[Guest]: He didn't set up a school.

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:16.040
[Guest]: He didn't do anything.

00:53:16.040 --> 00:53:19.360
[Guest]: Sharad Pawar has done much of it, you know, although it is under the radar.

00:53:19.360 --> 00:53:23.000
[Guest]: He doesn't tom-tom and he doesn't blow his own trumpet.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:27.320
[Guest]: But Maharashtrian, middle class Maharashtrian intellectuals wanted to identify more with

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:31.200
[Guest]: Sharad Pawar at that time, than with Bal Thackeray.

00:53:31.200 --> 00:53:34.760
[Guest]: And until he rejoined the Congress, because you know, these people, some of these people,

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:36.040
[Guest]: they don't like the Congress.

00:53:36.040 --> 00:53:38.320
[Guest]: They have never liked the Congress from the beginning.

00:53:38.320 --> 00:53:41.040
[Guest]: And they always wanted an alternative.

00:53:41.040 --> 00:53:45.320
[Guest]: So they thought that they were getting an alternative in Bal Thackeray, when they realized

00:53:45.320 --> 00:53:49.000
[Guest]: how violent and extortionist that party was and that they were not like that and they

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:50.000
[Guest]: didn't endorse that.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:53.200
[Guest]: They shifted to Sharad Pawar when he formed the Congress.

00:53:53.200 --> 00:53:59.600
[Guest]: When he came back to the Congress, many of them shifted back to the Shiv Sena.

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:04.320
[Guest]: By that time, the BJP was also kind of in alliance with the Shiv Sena.

00:54:04.320 --> 00:54:08.880
[Guest]: And if you notice, every other regional party, whether it is Telugu Desam in Andhra Pradesh

00:54:08.880 --> 00:54:16.480
[Guest]: or Ahom Ganapareesh in Assam, or even Trinamool Congress and Maya Vati, Mulayam Singh Yadav,

00:54:16.480 --> 00:54:21.520
[Guest]: all of them have come to power in their respective states within five years of their existence.

00:54:21.520 --> 00:54:27.000
[Guest]: You know, they formed a political party, maybe five years or at the most, the next term,

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.720
[Guest]: sixth year, seventh year, they have come to power.

00:54:29.720 --> 00:54:35.280
[Guest]: Shiv Sena is the only party which took 30 years to come to power in Maharashtra.

00:54:35.280 --> 00:54:37.920
[Guest]: And that too only in alliance with the BJP.

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:42.000
[Guest]: Because you know, they didn't look upon themselves as a political party and governing Maharashtra

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.280
[Guest]: was never their intention.

00:54:44.280 --> 00:54:45.920
[Guest]: Like I said, they were just extortionists.

00:54:45.920 --> 00:54:49.360
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they were collecting left, right and center.

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:51.040
[Guest]: That is all that they were interested in.

00:54:51.040 --> 00:54:54.260
[Guest]: You know, I mean, and Bal Thackeray was only interested in himself.

00:54:54.260 --> 00:54:56.120
[Guest]: He was not interested in anything else.

00:54:56.120 --> 00:55:00.060
[Guest]: You know, I mean, I would endorse Ajit Pawar that he never did anything for the people

00:55:00.060 --> 00:55:01.060
[Guest]: of Maharashtra.

00:55:01.060 --> 00:55:02.400
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's very interesting.

00:55:02.400 --> 00:55:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Like in your book, you point out how one point of disillusionment and obviously there was

00:55:06.320 --> 00:55:09.760
[Amit Varma]: a sense among many people that they're a B team of the Congress and the Congress is running

00:55:09.760 --> 00:55:10.760
[Amit Varma]: them.

00:55:10.760 --> 00:55:15.200
[Amit Varma]: But one major disillusionment came in 75 when Thackeray went on TV to support the emergency

00:55:15.200 --> 00:55:17.520
[Amit Varma]: after earlier having come out against it.

00:55:17.520 --> 00:55:18.520
[Guest]: Yes.

00:55:18.520 --> 00:55:20.560
[Guest]: And that is also because, you know, I mean, he was forced.

00:55:20.560 --> 00:55:21.560
[Guest]: S.B.

00:55:21.560 --> 00:55:28.200
[Guest]: Chavan was the chief minister and they sent a posse of policemen to Matushree.

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:32.400
[Guest]: And you know, Thackeray wanted to protect his magazine, Marmic.

00:55:32.400 --> 00:55:35.320
[Guest]: And all journals were being shut down at that point of time.

00:55:35.320 --> 00:55:36.960
[Guest]: He didn't want that to happen.

00:55:36.960 --> 00:55:40.280
[Guest]: So they gave him a choice, you know, I mean, saying that, you know, either you come with

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:45.280
[Guest]: us to Doordarshan and support the emergency or else we are taking you to jail and you

00:55:45.280 --> 00:55:46.280
[Guest]: will be shutting down Marmic.

00:55:46.280 --> 00:55:48.240
[Guest]: You know, so they gave him half an hour.

00:55:48.240 --> 00:55:50.760
[Guest]: He came out in 10 minutes and said, come, let's go to Doordarshan.

00:55:50.760 --> 00:55:52.760
[Guest]: And they shut down Marmic anyway.

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:53.760
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:55:53.760 --> 00:55:57.360
[Guest]: Later on, you know, I mean, so never trust the devil, as they say, you know, I mean,

00:55:57.360 --> 00:55:58.360
[Guest]: never believe in it.

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:02.120
[Guest]: But he wanted to protect Marmic and he was also afraid of jail, you know, because once

00:56:02.120 --> 00:56:07.040
[Guest]: he went to jail for three months in 1969 during the, you know, the Belgaum riots, anti-Muraji

00:56:07.040 --> 00:56:11.000
[Guest]: Desai riots, basically, you know, I mean, they wanted to stop Muraji Desai and give

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:15.240
[Guest]: him a petition and Desai did not want to stop and he ran his vehicle over some ships and

00:56:15.240 --> 00:56:16.240
[Guest]: etc.

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:20.160
[Guest]: So everybody went on rampage and then they arrested Thackeray and put him in prison and

00:56:20.160 --> 00:56:22.480
[Guest]: he didn't like that experience of three months.

00:56:22.480 --> 00:56:25.120
[Guest]: So he didn't want to go to jail, you know, I mean, so he preferred, you know, and he

00:56:25.120 --> 00:56:28.760
[Guest]: supported and actually the opposition was very disappointed because at that point of

00:56:28.760 --> 00:56:30.640
[Guest]: time, they had needed Thackeray's firepower.

00:56:30.640 --> 00:56:35.480
[Guest]: They had needed his foot soldiers and then suddenly the foot soldiers were not available,

00:56:35.480 --> 00:56:39.960
[Guest]: you know, I mean, and he had supported the Congress, but he had supported Indira Gandhi.

00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:45.640
[Guest]: He also met Indira Gandhi during the emergency and Mrs. Gandhi also struck the Shiv Sena

00:56:45.640 --> 00:56:49.120
[Guest]: off the banned parties list after meeting Bal Thackeray.

00:56:49.120 --> 00:56:51.160
[Guest]: So there was a quid pro quo there.

00:56:51.160 --> 00:56:56.560
[Guest]: But after she died, he did not feel obliged to support the Congress anymore.

00:56:56.560 --> 00:57:03.200
[Guest]: So if you see there is a shift in his philosophy from region to religion from 1984 onwards

00:57:03.200 --> 00:57:10.520
[Guest]: and from 1984 to about 1987, when there was a by-election in Vilepally in Mumbai, Dr.

00:57:10.520 --> 00:57:13.080
[Guest]: Ramesh Prabhu was contesting that election.

00:57:13.080 --> 00:57:18.520
[Guest]: He became a very sharp Hindutva wadi and his Hindutva was even too sharp for the BJP at

00:57:18.520 --> 00:57:19.720
[Guest]: that point of time.

00:57:19.720 --> 00:57:25.440
[Guest]: The BJP had just come out of this Janata Dal experiment, you know, I mean 1978 etc.

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:30.280
[Guest]: They had supported a Janata party candidate and Congress was contesting and Shiv Sena

00:57:30.280 --> 00:57:36.080
[Guest]: was contesting and Bal Thackeray made these very, very incendiary speeches against Muslims

00:57:36.080 --> 00:57:37.080
[Guest]: etc.

00:57:37.080 --> 00:57:45.960
[Guest]: And he has the record of being the first Indian to be disenfranchised by the Election Commission

00:57:45.960 --> 00:57:52.640
[Guest]: for basing his election campaign on religion rather than on secular issues.

00:57:52.640 --> 00:57:57.320
[Guest]: But his campaign was in 1987, but it took 10 years for the decision to come.

00:57:57.320 --> 00:58:01.640
[Guest]: So he was disenfranchised for six years and he couldn't vote until 2004.

00:58:01.640 --> 00:58:04.640
[Guest]: And so was Mr. Ramesh Prabhu.

00:58:04.640 --> 00:58:07.840
[Guest]: It destroyed Ramesh Prabhu's career, but it didn't make any difference to Bal Thackeray

00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:10.320
[Guest]: because he was not contesting elections anyway.

00:58:10.320 --> 00:58:12.080
[Guest]: And he continued with the same thing.

00:58:12.080 --> 00:58:17.160
[Guest]: But you know what happened is after 87, after his sharp Hindutva focus, then Pramod Mahajan,

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:20.240
[Guest]: you know, I mean realized that, you know, they were also going, BJP was also shifting

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:22.760
[Guest]: towards a sharp Mandir focus etc.

00:58:22.760 --> 00:58:26.520
[Guest]: And he said that we don't want our Hindutva votes to be divided.

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:30.280
[Guest]: They came together and it is in complete with Pramod Mahajan that Thackeray realized the

00:58:30.280 --> 00:58:34.960
[Guest]: value of really seriously fighting the Assembly elections and coming to government.

00:58:34.960 --> 00:58:39.080
[Guest]: So for the first time, usually he used to get only one MLA at a time in the Maharashtra

00:58:39.080 --> 00:58:40.080
[Guest]: Assembly.

00:58:40.080 --> 00:58:44.440
[Guest]: You know, I mean, in 1990 for the first time in alliance with the BJP, he got about 80

00:58:44.440 --> 00:58:46.080
[Guest]: or 85 MLAs.

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:50.800
[Guest]: And then the next election, 95, he managed to get a government.

00:58:50.800 --> 00:58:55.680
[Amit Varma]: So you know, we will talk about 1980s politics and the rise of the BJP and also the cooperative

00:58:55.680 --> 00:58:58.280
[Amit Varma]: movement and the part that played in politics after the break.

00:58:58.280 --> 00:59:01.520
[Amit Varma]: But before we go to the break, you know, you knew these people very well.

00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:03.360
[Amit Varma]: For example, you knew Bal Thackeray very well.

00:59:03.360 --> 00:59:04.720
[Amit Varma]: You interviewed him countless times.

00:59:04.720 --> 00:59:08.040
[Amit Varma]: If I remember correctly, you broke the news to him that the Babri Masjid has broken and

00:59:08.040 --> 00:59:10.400
[Unknown]: people are saying that Shiv Sinha has done it.

00:59:10.400 --> 00:59:15.120
[Amit Varma]: So in your personal interactions with him, and I'm assuming after a while, like, was

00:59:15.120 --> 00:59:17.560
[Amit Varma]: there some kind of friendship developing there?

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:23.560
[Amit Varma]: And did you find that in person he was reflective about what he was doing?

00:59:23.560 --> 00:59:25.360
[Amit Varma]: Or was he always drunk on his Kool-Aid?

00:59:25.360 --> 00:59:28.600
[Amit Varma]: Or was he always putting up a front for everybody, including you?

00:59:28.600 --> 00:59:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Or was he reflective?

00:59:29.600 --> 00:59:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Did he realize the mistakes he had made?

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.640
[Amit Varma]: Did he regret things he had done?

00:59:34.640 --> 00:59:37.600
[Guest]: I used to have a love-hate relationship with him.

00:59:37.600 --> 00:59:41.000
[Guest]: You know, I never agreed on certain issues.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:43.800
[Guest]: But maybe, maybe there were some things that I agreed with him.

00:59:43.800 --> 00:59:48.000
[Guest]: For example, when he said that, you know, I mean, do only criminals have human rights?

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:51.080
[Guest]: You know, I mean, and the victims don't have human rights.

00:59:51.080 --> 00:59:55.160
[Guest]: Yes, I could not disagree with him over there.

00:59:55.160 --> 01:00:00.520
[Guest]: But you know, and then once I challenged him, I said, how can you label all Muslims as anti-national?

01:00:00.520 --> 01:00:03.160
[Guest]: And how can you label all Muslims as terrorists?

01:00:03.160 --> 01:00:07.520
[Guest]: And there is an Abdul Hamid also, you know, I mean, the famous Abdul Hamid, you know,

01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:10.640
[Guest]: who fought against Pakistan on the border.

01:00:10.640 --> 01:00:14.560
[Guest]: He was killed and posthumously awarded the Paramvit Chakra, etc.

01:00:14.560 --> 01:00:16.600
[Guest]: So he said, yes, I have to make a difference.

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:20.400
[Guest]: I have to make a difference between loyal Muslims and disloyal Muslims.

01:00:20.400 --> 01:00:25.480
[Guest]: But if they want to stay in this country, and if they want to, you know, part of our

01:00:25.480 --> 01:00:30.640
[Guest]: gross national product, you know, the gross domestic product, then they have to act like

01:00:30.640 --> 01:00:33.480
[Guest]: Indians, which was also an acceptable thing.

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:37.320
[Guest]: You know, I mean, like, like, you can't have anybody living here in being a terrorist,

01:00:37.320 --> 01:00:40.520
[Guest]: you know, I mean, you have to follow the laws, you have to follow the rules.

01:00:40.520 --> 01:00:43.920
[Guest]: But I personally would not make a difference between the religions.

01:00:43.920 --> 01:00:46.320
[Guest]: Tapri used to make a difference on that between the religions.

01:00:46.320 --> 01:00:51.080
[Guest]: But this was before a lot of Saffron terrorism came to light, you know, I mean, so, so I

01:00:51.080 --> 01:00:55.080
[Guest]: could not argue with him on that, you know, by the time the Saffron terrorism came to

01:00:55.080 --> 01:00:58.520
[Guest]: light, he was a very sick man, he was always in hospital, you know, I mean, I never got

01:00:58.520 --> 01:01:02.920
[Guest]: a chance to go and have those long conversations with him that I had had in the 80s and the

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:04.640
[Amit Varma]: 90s, etc.

01:01:04.640 --> 01:01:06.720
[Amit Varma]: And was he someone who read books a lot?

01:01:06.720 --> 01:01:10.520
[Amit Varma]: Or, you know, I mean, what was his intellectual engagement with the world per se?

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:11.520
[Amit Varma]: Did he read books?

01:01:11.520 --> 01:01:14.520
[Amit Varma]: Were there thinkers he was influenced by?

01:01:14.520 --> 01:01:20.960
[Guest]: You know, he had the advantage of having a lot of, like I said, the Maharashtrian intellectuals,

01:01:20.960 --> 01:01:24.800
[Guest]: the early days, you know, like Dr. Ramesh Prabhu, he was a medical doctor, he was his

01:01:24.800 --> 01:01:29.400
[Guest]: private physician, you know, he joined the Shiv Sena, the day Thackeray held that rally

01:01:29.400 --> 01:01:32.800
[Guest]: in Shivaji Park, he signed up for the Shiv Sena.

01:01:32.800 --> 01:01:36.760
[Guest]: And then he got noticed by Bal Thackeray and Thackeray called him home and he became Thackeray's

01:01:36.760 --> 01:01:37.760
[Guest]: physician.

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:41.280
[Guest]: So they were lawyers, they were professors, they were doctors, they were engineers, all

01:01:41.280 --> 01:01:45.080
[Guest]: these kind of people who joined and I'm sure they gave him inputs.

01:01:45.080 --> 01:01:46.680
[Guest]: I'm sure they gave him inputs.

01:01:46.680 --> 01:01:49.880
[Guest]: But like I said, he alienated all of these people.

01:01:49.880 --> 01:01:54.280
[Guest]: And he decided to focus more on the lumpens, you know, he got a lot more out of the lumpens

01:01:54.280 --> 01:01:56.200
[Guest]: and he got out of these intellectuals.

01:01:56.200 --> 01:01:58.320
[Guest]: But I don't think he was very fond of reading.

01:01:58.320 --> 01:02:03.480
[Guest]: I don't think he, you know, because he was never taken to quoting and things like that.

01:02:03.480 --> 01:02:05.720
[Guest]: But then he would say Hitler was a nationalist.

01:02:05.720 --> 01:02:07.000
[Guest]: I believe in Hitler.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:10.000
[Guest]: He never read Hitler to know what Hitler had done.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:14.280
[Guest]: And then when you challenged him and you said, do you know what he did to the Jews?

01:02:14.280 --> 01:02:17.640
[Guest]: And he equated the Jews only with the Muslims, you know, and then when you told him that

01:02:17.640 --> 01:02:22.280
[Guest]: the Jews at that point of time were all intellectuals, they were professors, they were doctors, you

01:02:22.280 --> 01:02:26.200
[Guest]: know, I mean, they were philosophers, they were scientists, you know, he was a little

01:02:26.200 --> 01:02:27.200
[Guest]: taken aback.

01:02:27.200 --> 01:02:29.120
[Guest]: He said, really, they were not always like this.

01:02:29.120 --> 01:02:33.120
[Guest]: I said, no, they had to become like this because of what happened during the Holocaust.

01:02:33.120 --> 01:02:37.160
[Guest]: You know, I mean, they were not militant because, you know, Israel is now a very militant country,

01:02:37.160 --> 01:02:40.720
[Guest]: you know, I mean, so and I told him that, you know, Israel has to be like that because

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:44.960
[Guest]: it is surrounded on all sides by Islamic nations, you know, I mean, so they have to do something

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:48.560
[Guest]: to keep their heads above water, you know, but they were not like that always.

01:02:48.560 --> 01:02:49.840
[Guest]: And they were taken advantage of.

01:02:49.840 --> 01:02:51.440
[Guest]: So he would be taken aback a little bit.

01:02:51.440 --> 01:02:54.520
[Guest]: So I don't think he really actually bothered to read.

01:02:54.520 --> 01:02:58.480
[Guest]: But there were people who were feeding him a lot of information, including from newspapers,

01:02:58.480 --> 01:03:03.800
[Guest]: he would always have a lot of clippings marked in red and things like that with him.

01:03:03.800 --> 01:03:05.840
[Amit Varma]: So he had a lot of inputs.

01:03:05.840 --> 01:03:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And then attraction towards intellectuals like even Suresh Prabhu, who later on when

01:03:09.120 --> 01:03:14.640
[Amit Varma]: he brought him into the party and, you know, insisted that he become a minister in the

01:03:14.640 --> 01:03:16.600
[Unknown]: central government and so on.

